 The Circular Singly-linked List
The Josephus problem can be modeled by a circular linked list in which all nodes are linked in a continuous circle, without using null.  If we want to make a circular linked list storing B-C-D-E-F, most people will make "first" point to "B", as shown in the arrangement at the top.  In that case,
1. What is the Big-O to print the list? __________________

B

C

D

E

F

last
2. What is the Big-O to insert a "G" at the end, after the "F"? _________  
 
Now consider the arrangement of the nodes as shown at the bottom:  
3. What is the Big-O to print the list?___________  
4. What is the Big-O to insert a "G" at the end, after the "F"? ______    
 
➔ The list is B-C-D-E-F, but it is stored and processed as F-B-C-D-E for Big-O reasons.  
 
 
Josephus Lab Parts I and II
We will divide this program into two parts.  In the first part write the print and insert methods and test them.  The list is stored as F-B-C-D-E but it is printed as B-C-D-E-F.
 
